---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';
import Header from '../../components/Header.astro';
import Footer from '../../components/Footer.astro';
---

<Layout
  title="DRAW — Cecilia Ceballos"
  description="DRAW: A UI/UX case study helping people who keep giving up on drawing. By Cecilia Ceballos."
>
  <Header />

  <main class="case-study">
    <!-- ── Slide 1: Hero ───────────────────────────────── -->
    <div class="slide">
      <div class="col col--text">
        <p class="s-pretitle">DRAW:</p>
        <p class="s-tagline">Helping people who keep giving up on drawing</p>
      </div>
      <div class="col col--img col--contain">
        <img
          src="/images/draw/hero.jpg"
          alt="DRAW app shown on a phone resting in a sketchbook"
          loading="eager"
        />
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- ── Slide 2: The cycle ──────────────────────────── -->
    <div class="slide">
      <div class="col col--text">
        <h2 class="s-heading">The cycle everyone knows</h2>
        <div class="s-body">
          <p>You download a tutorial app.</p>
          <p>Watch a few videos.</p>
          <p>Try to follow along.</p>
          <p>Your sketch looks nothing like the instructor's.</p>
          <p>You check Instagram, see flawless illustrations, and think:</p>
          <p><em>I'll never get there.</em></p>
          <p>A week passes. You haven't touched your sketchbook.</p>
          <p>
            This cycle repeats for millions of aspiring artists, I designed
            <strong>Draw</strong> to break it.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="col col--img col--cover">
        <img
          src="/images/draw/s2-photo.jpg"
          alt="Sketchbook open on a desk with drawing tools"
        />
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- ── Slide 3: What I set out to learn ───────────── -->
    <div class="slide">
      <div class="col col--text">
        <h2 class="s-heading">What I set out to learn</h2>
        <div class="s-body">
          <p>
            Before designing anything, I needed to understand why this cycle
            keeps happening.
          </p>
          <p><strong>The research</strong></p>
          <ul>
            <li>
              Secondary research on habit formation and creative skill
              development.
            </li>
            <li>
              5 in-depth interviews with people trying to improve their drawing
              skills.
            </li>
            <li>Affinity mapping to find patterns across all the data.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="col col--img col--contain">
        <img
          src="/images/draw/s3-interviews.jpg"
          alt="Three video call interview screenshots with research participants"
        />
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- ── Slide 4: What the research revealed ────────── -->
    <div class="slide">
      <div class="col col--text">
        <h2 class="s-heading">What the research revealed</h2>
        <div class="s-body">
          <p>
            The real barriers aren't what you'd expect. People don't fail
            because they lack talent or tutorials.
          </p>
          <p>They fail because:</p>
          <ul>
            <li>They believe improvement requires hours they don't have.</li>
            <li>
              They measure success by the wrong metric. Every practice session
              gets judged by the final drawing. Bad result = motivation gone.
            </li>
            <li>
              They have no way to see their own progress. Without visible
              improvement, consistency feels pointless.
            </li>
            <li>
              Online content helps and hurts; endless tutorials create
              overwhelm, polished social media art creates impossible standards.
            </li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="col col--img col--contain">
        <img
          src="/images/draw/s4-affinity.jpg"
          alt="Affinity map showing research findings organised by theme"
        />
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- ── Slide 5: Two people, one problem ───────────── -->
    <div class="slide">
      <div class="col col--text">
        <h2 class="s-heading">Two people, one problem</h2>
        <div class="s-body">
          <p>From the research, two distinct users emerged:</p>
          <p><strong>Antonella, the aspiring professional</strong></p>
          <p>
            Graphic designer in New York. Dreams of freelance illustration.
            Follows artists on Instagram and feels miles behind. Believes she
            needs hours of practice to catch up. Draws every other week,
            frustrated each time.
          </p>
          <p><strong>Nick, the screen-fatigued explorer</strong></p>
          <p>
            Marketing professional, fully remote. Spends evenings scrolling.
            Remembers loving to draw as a kid. Wants an analog hobby but doesn't
            know where to start. Lower pressure, but still compares himself to
            what he sees online.
          </p>
          <p>Different motivations. Same pain points.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="col col--img col--contain">
        <img
          src="/images/draw/s5-research.jpg"
          alt="User persona illustrations for Antonella and Nick"
        />
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- ── Slide 6: Reframing the problem ─────────────── -->
    <div class="slide">
      <div class="col col--text">
        <h2 class="s-heading">Reframing the problem</h2>
        <div class="s-body">
          <p>
            The interviews made something clear: users don't just want to "learn
            to draw." They want to:
          </p>
          <ul>
            <li>Live more creative lives.</li>
            <li>Feel like they're growing.</li>
            <li>Have a richer analog life.</li>
          </ul>
          <p><strong>The questions I needed to answer</strong></p>
          <ul>
            <li>
              How might we show people that short, consistent practice beats
              long, sporadic sessions?
            </li>
            <li>
              How might we shift focus from end results to the act of
              practicing?
            </li>
            <li>
              How might we make progress visible without enabling comparison?
            </li>
            <li>How might we give structure without removing the joy?</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="col col--img col--cover">
        <img
          src="/images/draw/s6-persona.jpg"
          alt="Photo of a person drawing in a sketchbook"
        />
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- ── Slide 7: Designing the solution ────────────── -->
    <div class="slide">
      <div class="col col--text">
        <h2 class="s-heading">Designing the solution</h2>
        <div class="s-body">
          <p><strong>Four core tasks for the MVP</strong></p>
          <ol>
            <li>
              Create a personalized routine: adapting to time, interests, and
              skill level.
            </li>
            <li>Stay accountable: tracking consistency, not perfection.</li>
            <li>Get guidance: structured practices, not endless browsing.</li>
            <li>See progress: comparing to yourself, not others.</li>
          </ol>
          <p><strong>From flows to screens</strong></p>
          <p>
            I started with user flows, then sketched on paper, then moved to
            digital wireframes. Each round stripped away anything that didn't
            directly help the user succeed.
          </p>
          <p>
            The test I applied to every element: Does this help them practice,
            or distract from it?
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="col col--img col--contain">
        <img
          src="/images/draw/s7-solution.jpg"
          alt="Sketchbook with hand-drawn wireframes and user flow diagrams"
        />
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- ── Slide 8: 2×2 wireframe sketchbook grid ──────── -->
    <!--   Desktop: 4 individual rotated photos in CSS grid  -->
    <!--   Mobile:  composite mobile screenshot              -->
    <div class="slide slide--2x2">
      <div class="s8-grid">
        <div class="s8-cell">
          <div class="s8-rotated">
            <img
              src="/images/draw/s8-wire-1.jpg"
              alt="Hand-drawn wireframes: routine setup flow"
              loading="lazy"
            />
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="s8-cell">
          <div class="s8-rotated">
            <img
              src="/images/draw/s8-wire-2.jpg"
              alt="Hand-drawn wireframes: daily practice flow"
              loading="lazy"
            />
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="s8-cell">
          <div class="s8-rotated">
            <img
              src="/images/draw/s8-wire-3.jpg"
              alt="Hand-drawn wireframes: practice library flow"
              loading="lazy"
            />
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="s8-cell">
          <div class="s8-rotated">
            <img
              src="/images/draw/s8-wire-4.jpg"
              alt="Hand-drawn wireframes: progress tracking flow"
              loading="lazy"
            />
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- ── Slide 9: 4 digital wireframe screens ──────────── -->
    <div class="slide slide--s9">
      <!-- Mobile composite (shown ≤768px, hidden on desktop) -->
      <img
        class="s9-mobile"
        src="/images/draw/mobile/slide-09.png"
        alt="Four digital wireframe screens"
        loading="lazy"
      />
      <!-- Desktop: individual wireframe images in a row -->
      <div class="s9-row">
        <img
          src="/images/draw/s9-wire-1.png"
          alt="Dashboard wireframe screen"
          loading="lazy"
          class="s9-img"
        />
        <img
          src="/images/draw/s9-wire-2.png"
          alt="Practice selection wireframe screen"
          loading="lazy"
          class="s9-img"
        />
        <img
          src="/images/draw/s9-wire-3.png"
          alt="Lesson detail wireframe screen"
          loading="lazy"
          class="s9-img"
        />
        <img
          src="/images/draw/s9-wire-4.png"
          alt="Routine setup wireframe screen"
          loading="lazy"
          class="s9-img"
        />
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- ── Slide 10: Giving Draw a personality ──────────── -->
    <div class="slide slide--green">
      <div class="col col--text">
        <h2 class="s-heading">Giving Draw a personality</h2>
        <div class="s-body">
          <p>The visual identity needed to say: Relax. This is play, not pressure.</p>
          <ul>
            <li>
              <strong>Logo:</strong> A pencil doodle that forms the word
              "Draw".
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>Colors:</strong> Vibrant and unexpected, creativity
              should feel energising.
            </li>
            <li><strong>Shapes:</strong> Round, soft, approachable.</li>
            <li>
              <strong>Illustrations:</strong> Hand-drawn marks that celebrate
              imperfection.
            </li>
          </ul>
          <p>
            The goal was to make users feel free to experiment. No judgment.
            No comparison. Just practice.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="col col--logo">
        <img
          src="/images/draw/s10-logo.svg"
          alt="Draw logo — a pencil doodle forming the word DRAW"
          loading="lazy"
        />
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- ── Slide 11: Design system ──────────────────────── -->
    <div class="slide slide--s11">
      <!-- Left: colour palette SVG + component mockup -->
      <div class="s11-left">
        <img
          src="/images/draw/s11-palette.svg"
          alt="DRAW colour palette"
          class="s11-palette"
          loading="lazy"
        />
        <img
          src="/images/draw/s11-component.png"
          alt="DRAW typography and component system"
          class="s11-component"
          loading="lazy"
        />
      </div>
      <!-- Right: 2×2 grid of hand-drawn illustrations -->
      <div class="s11-right">
        <div class="s11-grid">
          <div class="s11-cell">
            <img src="/images/draw/s11-illus-1.png" alt="Hand-drawn building illustration" loading="lazy" />
          </div>
          <div class="s11-cell">
            <img src="/images/draw/s11-illus-2.png" alt="Hand-drawn nature landscape illustration" loading="lazy" />
          </div>
          <div class="s11-cell">
            <img src="/images/draw/s11-illus-3.png" alt="Hand-drawn figure in motion illustration" loading="lazy" />
          </div>
          <div class="s11-cell">
            <img src="/images/draw/s11-illus-4.png" alt="Hand-drawn still life illustration" loading="lazy" />
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- ── Slide 12: The final product ───────────────────── -->
    <picture class="slide-screenshot-wrap">
      <source
        media="(max-width: 768px)"
        srcset="/images/draw/mobile/slide-12.png"
      />
      <img
        src="/images/draw/slide-12.png"
        alt="The final product: high-fidelity screens for all four core flows"
        loading="lazy"
      />
    </picture>

    <!-- ── Slide 13: 4-phone hi-fi grid ──────────────────── -->
    <picture class="slide-screenshot-wrap">
      <source
        media="(max-width: 768px)"
        srcset="/images/draw/mobile/slide-13.png"
      />
      <img
        src="/images/draw/slide-13.png"
        alt="Four hi-fidelity phone screens displayed side by side"
        loading="lazy"
      />
    </picture>

    <!-- ── Slide 14: Testing with real users ─────────────── -->
    <picture class="slide-screenshot-wrap">
      <source
        media="(max-width: 768px)"
        srcset="/images/draw/mobile/slide-14.png"
      />
      <img
        src="/images/draw/slide-14.png"
        alt="Usability testing findings from round one and round two"
        loading="lazy"
      />
    </picture>

    <!-- ── Slide 15: 4-phone revised grid ────────────────── -->
    <picture class="slide-screenshot-wrap">
      <source
        media="(max-width: 768px)"
        srcset="/images/draw/mobile/slide-15.png"
      />
      <img
        src="/images/draw/slide-15.png"
        alt="Four phone screens showing the revised UI after testing"
        loading="lazy"
      />
    </picture>

    <!-- ── Slide 16: What I learned ───────────────────── -->
    <div class="slide">
      <div class="col col--text">
        <h2 class="s-heading">What I learned</h2>
        <ul class="s-body">
          <li>
            <strong>Research changes the problem.</strong> I started thinking users
            needed better content but they needed structure.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Personas are decision tools.</strong> Antonella and Nick helped
            me balance depth and approachability.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Subtraction is design work.</strong> Removing features that enable
            comparison was as important as building features that support practice.
          </li>
        </ul>
      </div>
      <div class="col col--img col--cover">
        <img
          src="/images/draw/s16-photo.jpg"
          alt="Hands holding an open sketchbook"
        />
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- ── Slide 17: Next steps ──────────────────────────── -->
    <picture class="slide-screenshot-wrap">
      <img
        src="/images/draw/slide-17.png"
        alt="Next steps: social features, streak recovery, and progress visualisation"
        loading="lazy"
      />
    </picture>

    <!-- ── Slide 18: Thank you ─────────────────────────── -->
    <div class="slide slide--reversed">
      <div class="col col--blank"></div>
      <div class="col col--text col--text-right">
        <h2 class="s-heading s-heading--right">Thank You</h2>
        <ul class="s-body">
          <li>Tools used: Figma, FigJam, Quicktime</li>
          <li>
            Methods: Secondary research, user interviews, affinity mapping,
            personas, HMW statements, flowcharts, wireframes, hi-fi mockups,
            user testing.
          </li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- ── Contact section ────────────────────────────── -->
    <section class="contact" aria-label="Contact">
      <h2 class="contact__heading">Let's work together</h2>
      <p class="contact__body">
        I'm currently looking for full-time UI/UX design roles. If you think I'd
        be a good fit for your team, I'd love to hear from you.
      </p>
      <a href="mailto:studio@ceciliaceballos.com" class="contact__email">
        studio@ceciliaceballos.com
      </a>
    </section>
  </main>

  <Footer />
</Layout>

<style>
  /* ── Case study wrapper ──────────────────────────────── */
  .case-study {
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    align-items: center;
    gap: 40px;
    padding: 40px 40px 0;
    background: #fff;
  }

  /* ── HTML Slide ──────────────────────────────────────── */
  .slide {
    display: flex;
    width: 100%;
    max-width: 1360px;
    min-height: 765px;
    background: #fff;
  }

  /* Column: text */
  .col--text {
    flex: 0 0 50%;
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    justify-content: center;
    gap: 24px;
    padding: 80px 52px;
    background: #fff;
  }

  /* Column: image */
  .col--img {
    flex: 0 0 50%;
    position: relative;
    overflow: hidden;
  }
  .col--img img {
    position: absolute;
    inset: 0;
    width: 100%;
    height: 100%;
    max-width: none;
    display: block;
  }
  .col--cover img {
    object-fit: cover;
    object-position: top center;
  }
  .col--contain img {
    object-fit: contain;
  }

  /* Blank column (slide 18 left side) */
  .col--blank {
    flex: 0 0 50%;
    background: #fff;
  }

  /* Slide 18: reversed layout — text is right-aligned */
  .col--text-right {
    gap: 80px; /* Figma: gap-[80px] for thank-you slide */
  }
  .s-heading--right {
    text-align: right;
  }

  /* ── Screenshot slides (wrapped in <picture>) ───────── */
  .slide-screenshot-wrap {
    display: block;
    width: 100%;
    max-width: 1360px;
    align-self: center;
  }
  .slide-screenshot-wrap img {
    display: block;
    width: 100%;
    height: auto;
  }

  /* ── Slide 8: 2×2 wireframe photo grid ──────────────── */
  /*   Matches Figma: grid 1068×753 at left:146 top:29     */
  .slide--2x2 {
    /* Override .slide flex layout */
    display: block;
    position: relative;
    height: 765px;
    min-height: unset;
    overflow: hidden;
    background: #fff;
  }

  .s8-grid {
    position: absolute;
    top: 29px;
    left: 146px;
    width: 1068px;
    height: 753px;
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr;
    grid-template-rows: 1fr 1fr;
    gap: 20px;
  }

  /* Each cell is a container so we can use cqw/cqh inside */
  .s8-cell {
    container-type: size;
    display: flex;
    align-items: center;
    justify-content: center;
    overflow: hidden;
  }

  /*
   * The scans are portrait (1976×2801) but were rotated −90° in Figma
   * so they appear landscape. We replicate that here:
   *   • width  = cell HEIGHT (before rotation, this is the short axis)
   *   • height = cell WIDTH  (before rotation, this is the long axis)
   * After rotate(−90deg) the element visually fills the cell correctly.
   */
  .s8-rotated {
    transform: rotate(-90deg);
    flex: none;
    width: 100cqh;
    height: 100cqw;
  }

  .s8-rotated img {
    width: 100%;
    height: 100%;
    object-fit: cover;
    object-position: center;
    display: block;
    max-width: none;
  }

  /* Mobile composite image — hidden on desktop */
  .s8-mobile {
    display: none;
  }

  /* ── Slide 9: 4 digital wireframe screens row ─────────── */
  /*   Matches Figma: flex row at left:52 top:106, gap:52     */
  /*   Each image: 275×597px                                  */
  .slide--s9 {
    display: block;
    position: relative;
    height: 765px;
    min-height: unset;
    overflow: hidden;
    background: #fff;
  }

  .s9-mobile {
    display: none;
  }

  .s9-row {
    position: absolute;
    top: 106px;
    left: 52px;
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: row;
    gap: 52px;
  }

  .s9-img {
    width: 275px;
    height: 597px;
    object-fit: cover;
    display: block;
    flex: none;
  }

  /* ── Slide 10: Giving Draw a personality ─────────────── */
  .slide--green .col--text,
  .slide--green .col--logo {
    background: #9cd08a;
  }

  .col--logo {
    flex: 0 0 50%;
    display: flex;
    align-items: center;
    justify-content: center;
  }

  .col--logo img {
    width: 269px;
    height: auto;
    display: block;
  }

  /* ── Slide 11: Design system ─────────────────────────── */
  /*   Left: 627px green panel — palette + component        */
  /*   Right: flex-1 green panel — 2×2 illustration grid    */
  .slide--s11 {
    height: 765px;
    min-height: unset;
    background: #9cd08a;
  }

  .s11-left {
    flex: 0 0 627px;
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    align-items: center;
    justify-content: center;
    gap: 38px;
    padding: 82px 111px;
    background: #9cd08a;
  }

  .s11-palette {
    width: 282px;
    height: auto;
    display: block;
  }

  .s11-component {
    width: 405px;
    height: auto;
    display: block;
  }

  .s11-right {
    flex: 1;
    position: relative;
    background: #9cd08a;
  }

  /* Grid: fills most of the right panel, 2-col 2-row */
  .s11-grid {
    position: absolute;
    inset: 32px 32px 32px 32px;
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr;
    grid-template-rows: 1fr 1fr;
    column-gap: 24px;
    row-gap: 24px;
  }

  .s11-cell {
    overflow: hidden;
  }

  .s11-cell img {
    width: 100%;
    height: 100%;
    object-fit: cover;
    object-position: center;
    display: block;
    max-width: none;
    mix-blend-mode: multiply;
  }

  /* ── Slide 1 hero typography ─────────────────────────── */
  .s-pretitle {
    font-family: 'League Spartan', sans-serif;
    font-weight: 700;
    font-size: 24px;
    letter-spacing: 3.6px;
    line-height: 1;
    color: #000;
  }
  .s-tagline {
    font-family: 'League Spartan', sans-serif;
    font-weight: 600;
    font-size: 20px;
    letter-spacing: -0.4px;
    line-height: 1.32;
    color: #000;
  }
  /* Slide 1 has smaller gap between pretitle and tagline */
  .slide:first-child .col--text {
    gap: 12px;
  }

  /* ── Standard slide heading ──────────────────────────── */
  .s-heading {
    font-family: 'League Spartan', sans-serif;
    font-weight: 700;
    font-size: 20px;
    letter-spacing: 2px;
    line-height: 1.2;
    color: #000;
  }

  /* ── Body text (Crimson Pro) ─────────────────────────── */
  .s-body {
    font-family: 'Crimson Pro', Georgia, serif;
    font-weight: 400;
    font-size: 16px;
    letter-spacing: -0.32px;
    line-height: 1.32;
    color: #000;
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: 8px;
  }
  .s-body p,
  .s-body li {
    margin: 0;
  }
  .s-body ul,
  .s-body ol {
    padding-left: 20px;
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: 4px;
  }
  /* When s-body is itself a ul (slide 16, 18) */
  ul.s-body {
    padding-left: 20px;
  }
  .s-body strong,
  .s-body b {
    font-weight: 700;
  }
  .s-body em {
    font-style: italic;
  }

  /* ── Contact Section ─────────────────────────────────── */
  .contact {
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: 32px;
    padding: 144px 120px;
    background: #fff;
    width: 100%;
    max-width: 1440px;
  }
  .contact__heading {
    font-family: 'League Spartan', sans-serif;
    font-weight: 500;
    font-size: 48px;
    letter-spacing: 2.4px;
    line-height: 1;
    color: #000;
    white-space: nowrap;
  }
  .contact__body {
    font-family: 'League Spartan', sans-serif;
    font-weight: 400;
